{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599543"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:57:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:57:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15580"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15580"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0,0.79,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8271"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47393"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5115"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman has blood tests that show an elevated serum calcium of 2.8 mmol/L (2.1-2.6). This triggers the release of a hormone from specialised cells in the thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormones is released from the thyroid gland in response to elevated serum calcium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcitriol","Transthyretin","Calcitonin","Triiodothyronine","Reverse-Triiodothyronine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen serum calcium levels rise, parafollicular C cells in the thyroid gland release \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcitonin\u003C/strong\u003E. This hormone acts to lower serum calcium through two main mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInhibition of osteoclast-mediated bone resorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased urinary calcium excretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcitriol\u003C/strong\u003E (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D) is produced by the kidneys and acts to increase calcium absorption. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransthyretin\u003C/strong\u003E is a transport protein for thyroid hormones. \u003Cstrong\u003ETriiodothyronine\u003C/strong\u003E (T3) and \u003Cstrong\u003Ereverse-Triiodothyronine\u003C/strong\u003E are produced from thyroxine (T4) and are not directly involved in calcium homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis feedback system operates independently of the hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis that regulates thyroid hormone production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcitonin is produced by parafollicular C cells of the thyroid gland in response to elevated serum calcium","Calcitonin acts to lower serum calcium by inhibiting bone resorption and increasing calcium excretion","The calcitonin feedback loop is independent of thyroid hormone production"],"references":["Lofrese JJ, Basit H, Lappin SL. Physiology, Parathyroid. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482510/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press. USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15580"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T20:43:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T09:49:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8271"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61947"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/